{{more citations|date=May 2018}}
[[File:La Cosmographie de Claude Ptolemée.djvu|page=9|thumb|right|''Geography'' by Ptolemy, Latin manuscript of the early 15th century, with maps by Claudius Clavus]]
'''Claudius Clavus''' (Suartho) also known as ''Nicholas Niger'', ({{lang-da|Claudius Claussøn Swart}}), (September 14, 1388-?), was a [[Denmark|Danish]] [[geographer]] sometimes considered to be the first [[Nordic Countries|Nordic]] [[cartographer]].<ref>[http://runeberg.org/dbl/3/0642.html Dansk Biografisk Leksikon]</ref><ref>[http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/04009b.htm Catholic Encyclopedia]</ref>

It is believed that he was born in the village of [[Salling (Funen)|Salling]] on the Danish island of [[Funen]]. He is commemorated by a plaque in the local ''Aagaarden''.

In 1412-13 at the age of 25 he started to travel around Europe and appeared eleven years later (1423–24) in [[Rome]]. It is believed he travelled as far north as the 70°10' N. [[latitude|lat.]] In Rome he became friends with the cardinal [[Giordano Orsini (died 1438)|Giordano Orsini]] and the pope's secretary [[Gian Francesco Poggio Bracciolini]], who were among those working to update the old Roman cartography. Claudius contributed to a more realistic description of Nordic countries, in particular [[Iceland]] and [[Greenland]], and was probably the first cartographer to put [[Greenland]] on a map. He is also known for having named Greenlandic places by using lyrics from old folk songs.

Unfortunately, most of his work (including two maps) is [[lost work| lost]], but a copy has been preserved through the German cartographers [[Donnus Nicholas Germanus]] and [[Henricus Martellus Germanus]], and in the nineteenth century more texts were rediscovered in the imperial library at [[Vienna]]. He drew 27 maps for a copy of the ''[[Geography (Ptolemy)|Geography]]'' by [[Claudius Ptolemy|Ptolemy]] (see image).

