{{Orphan|date=August 2018}}
{{Infobox person | name = Simone Strey | image = | alt = | caption = | birth_date = {{Birth year and age|1984}} | birth_place = [[Hanover]], [[Germany]] | residence = [[Berlin]], [[Germany]] | nationality = | ethnicity = | citizenship = | education = | alma_mater = [[University of Hanover]] | occupation = [[Entrepreneurship|Internet entrepreneur]] | years_active = | employer = | organization = | known_for = Co-founder and [[CEO]] of [[Plantix (mobile app)|Plantix]] | notable_works = | spouse = | partner = | children = | parents = | relatives = | awards = | website = {{URL|peat.technology}} | box_width = }}
'''Simone Strey''' is a German internet [[Entrepreneurship|entrepreneur]] who is co-founder and [[Chief executive officer|CEO]] of the mobile crop advisory app Plantix. For her work, she was honored with the [[TR35|Innovators under 35 Award]] by [[MIT Technology Review|MIT technology review]] in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heise.de/tr/artikel/Diagnose-per-Bilderkennung-3243259.html|title=Die Botanikerin Simone Strey (32) will Pflanzenkrankheiten besser diagnostizieren.|last=Stieler|first=Wolfgang|date=21 June 2016|website=heise.de|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=22 March 2018}}</ref>
== Early life and education == Strey was born and raised in [[Hanover]], [[Germany]]. She studied geography with a focus on [[geobotanic]] and soil science at the [[University of Hanover]].
== Career == As a PhD candidate, Strey worked on several scientific papers dealing with carbon stocks in soil and sustainable land use.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Strey et al.|first=Simone|date=January 2018|title=Seeing the forest not for the carbon: why concentrating on land-use-induced carbon stock changes of soils in Brazil can be climate-unfriendly|url=https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007%2Fs10113-016-1008-1|journal=Regional Environmental Change|volume=18|pages=63–75|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Strey et al.|first=Simone|date=January 2016|title=Future land use and land cover in Southern Amazonia and resulting greenhouse gas emissions from agricultural soils|url=https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s10113-017-1235-0|journal=Regional Environmental Change|volume=18|pages=129–142|via=}}</ref><ref name=":0">{{Cite journal|last=Strey et al.|first=Simone|date=19 October 2017|title=DIGGING DEEPER: THE VALUE OF DEEP SOIL CARBON FOR POTENTIAL REDD+ PROJECTS IN TROPICAL FOREST COMMUNITIES IN AMAZONIA|url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Jens_Boy/publication/319972294_Digging_deeper_The_value_of_deep_soil_carbon_for_potential_REDD_projects_in_tropical_forest_communities_in_Amazonia/links/59e8904c458515c363133ecd/Digging-deeper-The-value-of-deep-soil-carbon-for-potential-REDD-projects-in-tropical-forest-communities-in-Amazonia.pdf|journal=Erdkunde|volume=71|pages=231–239|via=}}</ref> In collaboration with the Mekranoti, an indigenous tribe of the [[Kayapo]] nation in [[Brazil|Brazil's]] [[Pará|Pará state]], she investigated the carbon content of the soil to a depth of {{Convert|10|m|}} in an untouched forest in Amazonia.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KIStcYWN4oM|title=Deep carbon stocks in the Brazilian Mekragnoti (Kayapó) territory – REDD|last=|first=|date=27 August 2016|work=Youtube|access-date=22 March 2018|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=}}</ref><ref name=":0" /> Strey was also co-founder of Green Desert e.V. in 2008 and has been chairman of the association since then. Green Desert is an [[Non-governmental organization|NGO]] committed to sustainable agriculture and open source technologies in [[The Gambia|Gambia]] and [[Senegal]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.langeleine.de/?p=4462|title=Großer Erfolg für Forschungsverein "Green Desert"|last=Smotlacha|first=Jörg|date=24 September 2008|website=langeleine.de|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=22 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=135TONB8rK8|title=Green Desert's Open Windpump Technology im NDR|last=|first=|date=15 August 2016|work=Youtube|access-date=22 March 2018|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=}}</ref>
=== Plantix === The idea for Plantix began in 2014 as a scientific crowdsourcing science project called "Garden Bank", which was initiated together with Robert Strey, Pierre Munzel, Charlotte Schumann, Alexander Kennepohl, Bianca Kummer and Korbinian Hartberger.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gruender.wiwo.de/peat-digitaler-pflanzendoktor-punktet-auf-cebit/|title=Peat: Digitaler Pflanzendoktor punktet auf der Cebit|last=|first=|date=20 March 2017|website=wiwo.de|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=22 March 2018}}</ref> As a consequence, Strey co-founded the PEAT [[Gesellschaft mit beschränkter Haftung|GmbH]], which is responsible for the Plantix app, with the above-mentioned team in 2015. Strey received the Exist startup scholarship for the idea of automated detection of plant diseases.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.exist.de/DE/Campus/Gruendergeist/EXIST-Erfolge/PEAT-GmbH/inhalt.html|title=PEAT-GmbH|last=|first=|date=May 2017|website=exist.de|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=22 March 2018}}</ref> At the end of 2017, Plantix had raised [[venture capital]] and successfully closed the [[Series A round|series A]] with [[Index Ventures|Index Venture]]. In the meantime the app reached the 1 million download mark on [[Google Play]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2018}} Plantix cooperates with international research institutes and inter-governmental organizations such as [[International Crops Research Institute for the Semi-Arid Tropics|ICRISAT]], [[International Maize and Wheat Improvement Center|CIMMYT]] and [[Centre for Agriculture and Bioscience International|CABI]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.icrisat.org/mobile-app-to-help-farmers-overcome-crop-damage/|title=Mobile App to Help Farmers Overcome Crop Damage|last=|first=|date=25 May 2017|website=icrisat.org|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=22 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cimmyt.org/project-profile/nepal-seed-and-fertilizer-project/|title=Nepal Seed and Fertilizer Project|last=|first=|date=2016|website=cimmyt.org|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=22 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cabi.org/news-and-media/2018/cabi-trials-peats-smartphone-app-plantix-that-identifies-plant-pests-in-the-field/|title=CABI trials PEAT's smartphone app Plantix that identifies plant pests in the field|last=|first=|date=2018|website=cabi.org|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=22 March 2018}}</ref>
