The following is a timeline of the [[Chemnitz#History|history]] of the city of [[Chemnitz]], [[Germany]]. {{Dynamic list}} {{TOC right}}
==Prior to 20th century== {{History of Germany}}
* 1136 - {{Interlanguage link multi|Benediktinerkloster Chemnitz|de|3=Benediktinerkloster Chemnitz|lt=Benedictine monastery}} founded near Chemnitz.{{sfn|Britannica|1910}} * 1143 - Chemnitz "becomes a market town."{{sfn|Britannica|1910}} * 1398 - [[Paper mill]] established.<ref name="Sandermann2013">{{cite book|author=Wilhelm Sandermann|title=Papier: Eine spannende Kulturgeschichte|year= 2013|publisher=Springer-Verlag|isbn=978-3-662-09193-7 |language=de |chapter=Beginn der Papierherstellung in einigen Landern }} (timeline)</ref> * 1466 - Population: 3,455. * 1498 - {{Interlanguage link multi|Altes Rathaus (Chemnitz)|de|3=Altes Rathaus (Chemnitz)|lt=Town Hall}} built near the {{Interlanguage link multi|Markt (Chemnitz)|de}}. * 1539 - [[Protestant Reformation]].{{sfn|Britannica|1910}} * 1551 - Population: 5,616. * 1630 - [[Battle of Chemnitz]]. * 1700 - Population: 4,873. * 1801 - Population: 10,835. * 1811 - Schwalbe manufactory in business (later {{Interlanguage link multi|Chemieanlagenbau Chemnitz|de}} engineering firm). * 1833 - {{Interlanguage link multi|Stadtorchester Chemnitz|de|3=Robert-Schumann-Philharmonie|lt=Chemnitz City Orchestra}} formed.<ref name="Lawson2003-19th">{{cite book|editor= [[Colin Lawson]] |title= Cambridge Companion to the Orchestra|year= 2003|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-00132-8 |chapter= Orchestras Founded in the 19th Century (chronological list) |chapterurl= https://books.google.com/books?id=1DW1WyiooSMC&pg=PA275 }}</ref> * 1836 - [[Chemnitz University of Technology|Royal Mercantile College]] established. * 1840 - Population: 23,476.{{sfn|Brockhaus|1896}} * 1852 - [[Chemnitz Hauptbahnhof]] opens. * 1864 - Population: 54,827.{{sfn|Brockhaus|1896}} * 1868 - {{Interlanguage link multi|Museum für Naturkunde Chemnitz|de}} founded. * 1869 - {{Interlanguage link multi|Volksbank Chemnitz|de}} (bank) founded. * 1878 - {{Interlanguage link multi|Jewish Cemetery, Chemnitz|de|3=Jüdischer Friedhof (Chemnitz)}} in use (approximate date). * 1880 ** Horsecar [[Trams in Chemnitz|tram]] begins operating. ** Population: 95,123.{{sfn|Brockhaus|1896}} ** {{Interlanguage link multi|Chemnitz-Schlosschemnitz|de|3=Chemnitz-Schloßchemnitz|lt=Schlosschemnitz}} becomes part of city. * 1884 - [[Chemnitz Tar Mummy]] discovered. * 1885 - Population: 110,817.<ref>{{cite book |title=Statesman's Year-Book |year=1890 |location=London |publisher= Macmillan and Co.|chapter= German Empire: Area and Population: Principal Towns |chapterurl= http://hdl.handle.net/2027/nyp.33433081590527?urlappend=%3Bseq=557 }}</ref> * 1888 - {{Interlanguage link multi|St. Peter's Church, Chemnitz|de|3=Petrikirche (Chemnitz)}} built. * 1890 - Population: 138,954.{{sfn|Brockhaus|1896}} * 1893 - Electric [[Trams in Chemnitz|tram]] begins operating. * 1899 - {{Interlanguage link multi|Chemnitz Synagogue|de|3=Alte Synagoge (Chemnitz)}} built.
==20th century== [[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 183-73766-0014, Karl-Marx-Stadt, II. FDGB-Arbeiterfestspiele, Rathaus.jpg|thumb|right|Arbeiterfestspiele participants in front of City Hall, 1960]] * 1905 - Population: 244,927.<ref>{{cite book |title=Statesman's Year-Book |year=1908 |location=London |publisher= Macmillan and Co.|chapter= Germany |chapterurl= http://hdl.handle.net/2027/nyp.33433081590592?urlappend=%3Bseq=1128 }}</ref> * 1907 - {{Interlanguage link multi|Chemnitz-Bernsdorf|de|3=Chemnitz-Bernsdorf|lt=Bernsdorf}} becomes part of city. * 1909 ** [[Chemnitz Opera]] hall built. ** {{Interlanguage link multi|König-Albert-Museum (Chemnitz)|de}} opens. * 1910 - [[Johann-Wolfgang-von-Goethe-Gymnasium]] (school) established. * 1911 - {{Interlanguage link multi|New City Hall, Chemnitz|de|3=Neues Rathaus (Chemnitz)}} built. * 1913 - {{Interlanguage link multi|Chemnitz-Borna-Heinersdorf|de|3=Chemnitz-Borna-Heinersdorf|lt=Borna-Heinersdorf}} becomes part of city. * 1919 - Population: 303,775.<ref>{{cite book |title=[[Statesman's Year-Book]] |year=1921 |location=London |publisher= Macmillan and Co.|chapter= Germany: Area and Population: Principal Towns |chapterurl= http://hdl.handle.net/2027/njp.32101072368440?urlappend=%3Bseq=972 |via=HathiTrust }}</ref> * 1920 - {{Interlanguage link multi|Chemnitzer Polizeisportverein|de}} sport club formed. * 1926 - [[Sportforum Chemnitz|Südkampfbahn]] stadium opens. * 1933 - {{Interlanguage link multi|Theaterplatz (Chemnitz)|de}} renamed "[[Adolf Hitler Platz]]". * 1934 - [[Stadion an der Gellertstraße]] (stadium) opens. * 1938 - 9 November: [[Kristallnacht]] antisemitic unrest; synagogue destroyed. * 1945 ** {{Interlanguage link multi|Bombing of Chemnitz in World War II|de|3=Luftangriffe auf Chemnitz}}. ** City becomes part of [[East Germany]]. * 1946 - Population: 250,188. * 1947 - [[Wismut (mining company)]] headquartered in Chemnitz. * 1950 - {{Interlanguage link multi|Chemnitz-Adelsberg|de|3=Chemnitz-Adelsberg|lt=Adelsberg}} becomes part of city. * 1953 - City renamed "Karl-Marx-Stadt". * 1955 - [[Botanischer Garten Chemnitz|Chemnitz Botanical Garden]] rebuilt.<ref name=botanic>{{cite web |url=http://www.bgci.org/garden_search.php?action=Find&ftrCountry=DE |title=Garden Search: Germany |publisher= [[Botanic Gardens Conservation International]] |location=London |accessdate=30 November 2015 }}</ref> * 1959 - {{Interlanguage link multi|Red Tower, Chemnitz|de|3=Roter Turm (Chemnitz)}} reconstructed. * 1960 - {{Interlanguage link multi|Arbeiterfestspiele|de|3=Arbeiterfestspiele der DDR}} (workers' cultural festival) held. * 1961 ** [[HKW Chemnitz-Nord]] power station begins operating. ** City [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with [[Tampere]], Finland. * 1966 ** [[Chemnitzer FC]] (football club) formed. ** City twinned with [[Ljubljana]], Yugoslavia. * 1967 - City twinned with [[Arras]], France. * 1968 - City twinned with [[Timbuktu]], Mali. * 1970 - City twinned with [[Ústí nad Labem]], Czechoslovakia. * 1971 - 9 October: [[Karl Marx Monument]] unveiled.<ref name=nyt2012 /> * 1972 ** City twinned with [[Łódź]], Poland. ** Population: 301,502. * 1974 - {{Interlanguage link multi|Wohngebiet Fritz Heckert|de}} (housing) construction begins. * 1990 ** City renamed "Chemnitz". ** {{Interlanguage link multi|Chemnitzer Verkehrs-Aktiengesellschaft|de}} (transit entity) established. ** Population: 294,244. * 1991 - Annual "Days of Jewish Culture" begins.<ref name=nyt1999>{{citation |work=New York Times |date= 28 June 1999 |title= Kurt Weill's Heritage: Honor Replaces Scorn; A German City Performs His Jewish Opera |url= https://www.nytimes.com/1999/06/28/theater/kurt-weill-s-heritage-honor-replaces-scorn-german-city-performs-his-jewish-opera.html?pagewanted=all }}</ref> * 1993 - {{Interlanguage link multi|Peter Seifert|de}} becomes mayor. * 1997 - [[City-Bahn Chemnitz]] (transit entity) established. * 1999 - {{Interlanguage link multi|Chemnitz-Röhrsdorf|de|3=Chemnitz-Röhrsdorf|lt=Röhrsdorf}} and {{Interlanguage link multi|Chemnitz-Wittgensdorf|de|3=Chemnitz-Wittgensdorf|lt=Wittgensdorf}} become part of city.
==21st century==
* 2001 - {{Interlanguage link multi|Villa Esche|de}} restored as a cultural space.<ref name=nyt2012>{{citation |work=New York Times |date= 27 July 2012 |title=In Germany, an Unlikely Art Hub Honed by Enthusiasm |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/07/28/arts/28iht-scgermany28.html?_r=0 }}</ref> * 2003 - {{Interlanguage link multi|Chemnitz Industrial Museum|de|3=Industriemuseum Chemnitz}} opens.{{Citation needed|date=November 2015}} * 2006 - {{Interlanguage link multi|Barbara Ludwig|de}} becomes mayor. * 2007 - [[Gunzenhauser Museum]] opens.<ref name=nyt2012 /> * 2010 - Population: 243,248. * 2012 - [[Thor Steinar]] "Brevik" shop in business.<ref>{{citation |work=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-17275627 |title=Furore over German 'Brevik' clothing shop in Chemnitz |date=6 March 2012 }}</ref> * 2014 - March: Neo-Nazi {{Interlanguage link multi|Nationale Sozialisten Chemnitz|de}} group banned.{{Citation needed|date=November 2015}}
